'''George Armour''' (April 24, 1812 - June 13, 1881) was a Scottish American businessman and philanthropist who transformed the global distribution process for commodities. He is credited with developing the [[grain elevator]] system, establishing grain trading standards as director and president of the [[Chicago Board of Trade]] (CBT), founding the [[Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad]] (CBQ), [[Commercial Club of Chicago]] , YMCA of Chicago, Merchants' Loan & Trust Company (MLTC), the precursor to [[Continental Illinois]],  and the [[Chicago Academy of Fine Arts]] which later became the [[School of the Art Institute of Chicago]] and [[Art Institute of Chicago]]. He served as a director of several notable companies during his career.

As founder of Armour, Dole & Co and other firms, he created the first extensive system of large mechanized [[grain elevator]]s in Chicago and thus enabled the shipment of grains from the American Midwest to destinations all over the world. During his tenure, the CBT standardized the grading and selling of grains and established the first commodity futures markets. He was "popularly known as the father of the grain elevator system"{{ sfn | Harper | Ravell |1907 | p = 68 }} or as a "rapacious, blood sucking insect."{{ sfn | Ely, Burnham & Bartlett | 1870 | p = 1629 }}

== Early life ==
[[File:Map-locating-first-cabins-argyle-illinois.png|left|thumb|Map locating first cabins Argyle, IL - includes location of cabin belonging to John and George Armour - ''circa'' 1830s {{sfn | Harvey | 1924 }}]]

George Armour was born on April 24, 1812 in [[Campbeltown]],[[Scotland]], on the [[Mull of Kintyre]].{{sfn|EncyclopediaChicago - Biographical Dictionary|2017 }}
Armour was a [[wheelwright]] and worked his way across the ocean as a shipboard [[Cooper (profession)|cooper]] or carpenter.{{ sfn | Harvey |1924 | p = 14 }}

In 1834, Armour with his brother John and cousin James a shoemaker, left Campbeltown and made a voyage to [[Ottawa, Illinois]].
Soon after their arrival in Ottawa, the brothers went north to what was then known as the "[[Argyle, Illinois|Argyle Settlement]]" near [[Rockford, Illinois]].
The brothers built a 14' x 14' cabin in hopes of establishing a timber and prairie land claim, but "farming was not to their liking."{{ sfn | Harvey |1924 | pp = 12-13 }}

In 1836, while on a trip to back to Scotland, the brothers helped their friend John Greenlee and his family escape from Campbeltown in order to avoid Greenlee being arrested by one of the [[Duke of Argyll]]'s tax collectors.
After the escape, the brothers furnished the Greenlees with passage to the US and set up the Greenlees in the cabin they had built in the Argyle Settlement.{{ sfn | Harvey |1924 | pp = 15 }} Subsequently, Armour lived in [[Joliet, Illinois|Joliet]] and [[Lockport, Illinois]] and entered the business of merchandising.{{ sfn| Chicago Tribune | 1881 }}
At the time, both cities were expanding rapidly because of the construction of the Illinois and Michigan Canal.{{ sfn | EncyclopediaChicago - Joliet |2017}} 
Lockport became headquarters for building the canal in 1837.{{ sfn | EncyclopediaChicago - Lockport |2017}}

[[File:Seneca IL Armour's Warehouse1.jpg|thumb| [[Armour's Warehouse]], Seneca, IL ]]
Later Armour became a sub-contractor with George Steel.{{ sfn| Chicago Tribune | 1881 }} Steel was born in [[Forfarshire]], Scotland in 1797 and arrived in Chicago in 1837.{{ sfn | MarketsWiki - George Steel | 2017 }} Steel had come to the US on contract for building a section of the Illinois & Michigan Canal but the work had stopped in the aftermath of the [[Panic of 1837]]. 
Steel and Armour built a section of the [[Illinois and Michigan Canal]] sometime between 1836 and 1848.{{sfn | Andreas Vol1| 1884 | p = 587 }}{{ sfn | Kirkland | 1919 | p = 57 }}
They also built a portion of the CBQ. The railroad was constructed starting in March 1848 and was completed in 1853.{{ sfn| Chicago Tribune | 1881 }}
Armour was a contractor for 16 miles (out of 181 miles) of road grading for the ROCK which started construction in 1851 and was completed by 1854.{{ sfn | Illinois ancestors | 2017 }} Armour most likely also worked on the [[Galena and Chicago Union Railroad]] - the first railroad built west of Chicago and a highly profitable venture that established [[William B. Ogden]] and [[George Smith (financier)|George Smith]] as major figures in Chicago history.{{ sfn | chapman| 1889 | p = 1041 }} Smith operated a "[[wildcat bank]]" that issued scrip which was used to pay workers - including Armour's employees.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p = 617}}

In the early 1850s, Armour resettled in Chicago.{{ sfn| Chicago Tribune | 1881 }} His brother John Armour remained in Ottawa where he became a successful businessman. Of John Armour's many investments, one that remains is [[Armour's Warehouse]]  built in 1861.{{ efn | Also known as the Seneca Grain Elevator or the Hogan's North Elevator, the structure is a historic grain elevator located in the village of [[Seneca, Illinois]], United States. The elevator and two surrounding outbuildings were listed on the U.S. National Register of Historic Places in 1997.}}{{ sfn | Library of Congress - Armour's Warehouse | 2017 }} In contrast, George Armour - in the following thirty years - went from being a foreman to being one of the richest and most influential businessmen in America.{{ efn | How Armour achieved his rags to riches life is hard to know. He appears to have arrived in America with a tradesman's education, limited access to capital and few social connections of any significance. It appears that Armour just happened to be the right person in the right place at the right time on a good number of occasions. }}
{{Clear|left}}

== Prospering in Chicago ==
[[File:ICHi-017111 - Chicago River.jpg|thumb|left|Munger & Armour grain elevator, Chicago, IL, 1868?]]
In Chicago, Armour reunited with George Steel - who had become a prosperous Chicago businessman. In 1852-1853 Steel was president of Chicago Board of Trade. In 1856, a new three-story building was erected on Steel's site: an office and warehouse located at the foot of LaSalle Street on South Street and this became the first permanent home for the CBT.{{ sfn | MarketsWiki - George Steel | 2014 }}{{ sfn | isas| 2014 }} Armour was an early member of the CBT and also commenced what became his signature venture - the erection and management of grain elevators.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}

Prior to Armour's efforts there had been a small number of what may be termed "grain elevators" constructed in the United States. [[Dart's Elevator]] was the world's first steam-powered grain elevator. It was designed and built by [[Joseph Dart]] and [[Robert Dunbar]] in 1842 in Buffalo, New York.
The first large steam elevator ever built in Chicago for handling grain from railroad tracks was on the North side, on the [[Chicago River]], west of Wells Street. It was built by George A Gibbs and E W Griffin of Gibbs, Griffin & Company in 1854.{{ sfn | Wright | 1868 | p=57}}{{ sfn | Kirkland | 1919 | p = 57 }} It might also have been known as the Chicago & Galena Union Railroad Elevator. {{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p = 374 }}

In 1854 George Steel took over a warehouse and built another grain elevator just west of the Gibbs, Griffin and Company warehouse. It was capable of operating from the canal as well as the railroads. The elevator had a capacity of 100,000 bushels and was located at Franklin and River streets - in the Chicago & Galena Union Railroad track on North Water Street.{{ sfn  | MarketsWiki - George Steel | 2014 }}

In that year Steel's warehouse burnt down{{ sfn | Andreas Vol1| 1884 | p = 587 }} and Steel sold the property to Wesley Munger and George Armour. Munger had owned a small mill at Waukegan, which had burned down.{{ sfn | Kirkland | 1919 | p = 57 }} As Munger & Armour,{{ sfn |  EncyclopediaChicago - Munger, Wheeler & Co | 2017 }} they built the first modern, steam-driven grain elevator in Chicago.{{ sfn | Chicago Tribune | 1868 }}{{ sfn | Chicago Tribune | 1881 }}{{ sfn | EncyclopediaChicago - Munger, Wheeler & Co | 2017 }} The grain elevator was completed in 1855 and had a capacity of 300,000 bushels.{{ sfn | taylor | 1917 | p = 201 }}

Armour's influence as a Chicago businessman grew and Armour was first elected a director of the CBT in 1856.{{ sfn | taylor| 1917 | p = 216 }}

In 1860 he joined with Charles Sydney Dole,{{ sfn | MacGrath | Reed | 1892 | p = 227 }} James Henry Doyle{{ sfn | MacGrath | Reed | 1902 | pp = 152-154 }} and Wesley Munger{{ sfn | EncyclopediaChicago - Armour Dole & Co  | 2017 }} and they formed Armour, Dole & Co.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p = 375 }} The company operated grain elevators at the depot of the CBQ with a capacity of 850,000 bushels. After the [[American Civil War]], Armour, Dole & Co. remained among the city's leading grain warehousers. Their elevators had a combined capacity of 2.1 million bushels in 1871. By the early 1880s, this figure had grown to 6.3 million bushels.{{ sfn | EncyclopediaChicago - Armour Dole & Co | 2017 }}

In 1863, Hiram Wheeler {{ sfn | MarketsWiki - Hiram Wheeler | 2013 }}{{ sfn | Andreas Vol1 | 1884 | p 587 }} entered the Munger & Armour, which then became Munger, Wheeler & Co.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p = 374 }} Armour remained a partner. The company owned large grain elevators next to the depot of the Chicago & North Western Railroad.{{ sfn | EncyclopediaChicago - Munger, Wheeler & Co | 2017 }}

At the Chicago Canal Convention of 1863,{{ sfn | nytimes | 1863 }} Armour was a member of the CBT delegation.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p = 349 }}{{ sfn | taylor | 1917 | p304}} 
The Convention proceedings called for laws and budgets to widen and deepen the [[Illinois and Michigan Canal]] and thus make it possible for ships to sail between the [[Great Lakes]] and the [[Mississippi River]].{{ sfn | Currey | 1912 | pp = 170-178 }}

=== Enablers of success ===
In order to succeed with a vision of moving of very numerous bushels of grain, Armour needed more than steam powered conveyor belts.{{ sfn | Cronon | 1991 | p = 120 }} He needed:

* Products that could be graded for quality according to industry-standards
* Banks that did not fail and supported stable currencies
* Futures exchange where contracts to buy specific quantities of a commodity or financial instrument at a specified price with delivery set at a specified time in the future

==== Industry-standard grading systems for grains ====
Through the 1830s sacks or barrels or even buckets of grain were hoisted off vessels and into warehouses by manpower - sometimes even using [[bucket brigade]]s.{{ sfn | Andreas Vol1 | 1884 | p = 579 }}{{ sfn | Pollan | 2006 | p = 59 }} The amounts of grain being moved in a contract were measured in the thousands of bushels. By the 1840s a certain amount of bulk transport was taking place and grain was stored in individual bins according to source in warehouses and the heavy lifting was done by [[block and tackle]] pulled by horses. By 1848 the horse was replaced by a steam engine, but not the block and tackle. The amounts being moved were in the tens of thousands of bushels.{{ sfn | taylor | 1917 | p = 144 }} If the transport of grain was to move into the hundreds of thousands of bushels then changes were needed.{{ sfn | EncyclopediaChicago - Agriculture | 2017 }}

When grains from multiple sources were to be co-mingled in silos holding hundred of thousands of bushels, then methods of grading and inspecting the quality of the grain are required.{{ sfn | Pollan | 2006 | p = 60 }}{{ sfn | Magrath | 1964 }} The CBT had been concerned with grading and inspecting products since the day it was founded.{{ sfn | taylor | 1917 | p = 138 }} In 1856 Armour was elected to the Board of Directors of the CBT.{{ sfn | taylor | 1917 | p = 216 }} In the same year, his partner Charles Dole was charged to set up a committee with the purpose of establishing grades by the separation of wheat into three industry-standard grades.{{ sfn | MacGrath | Reed | 1892 | p = 228}} By 1858 the grading and inspecting standards were established and compliance mechanisms set up.{{ sfn | MacGrath | Reed | 1892 | p = 227 }}{{ sfn | Wright | 1868 | p = 161 }} In 1859, the CBT received a state charter that enabled it to enforce grading standards and inspections with a legally binding basis. {{ sfn | santos | 2008 }}

==== Banks that do not fail ====
In banking, the period 1837 to 1863 is known as the "[[Free Banking]]" era. It was a period of "[[Wildcat Banks]]".{{ sfn | MLTC| 1901 | pp = 76-90 }} In the [[Panic of 1837]], out of 850 banks in the United States, 343 closed entirely, 62 failed partially.{{ sfn | Morris | 1914 | p = 136 }} If Armour's business was to prosper, he needed a bank that would not fail. In 1857, along with [[Cyrus McCormick]], who invented the [[reaper]], and Chicago's first mayor, [[William B. Ogden]], Armour was a founder and, later, elected director of the Merchants' Loan and Trust Company.{{ sfn | Chicago Tribune | 1994 }}{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | pp = 626-627 }} The book published by MLTC in 1907 titled ''Fifty Years of Banking in Chicago'' identified the banks' early mission:

{{ quote 
| text = The creation of the Merchants' Loan and Trust Company was the protest of Chicago's soundest businessmen and financiers against the continuance of irresponsible and unscientific banking.{{ sfn | Harper | Ravell | 1907 | p = 32 }}
}}

==== Fixed pricing by using futures contracts ====
In 1865 the CBT recognized the [[futures contract]] as a legitimate feature of trades and full rules were first established.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p = 357 }}{{ sfn | taylor | 1917 | p = 332 }} Given the increase in pricing certainty around the globe, Chicago grain elevator operators became free to construct grain elevators with capacities of millions of bushels.{{ sfn | Cronan | 1991 | p = 124 }}{{ sfn | santos | 2008 }}

==== And more ====
While the above three conditions may have been paramount in developing the grain warehousing business, there were a number of other hurdles to be cleared. The technology for moving grain had to improve and he development or trains, vessels and conveyors continued its rapid progress in typical nineteenth century fashion. Perhaps the most significant less obvious aspect was that the site and logistics planning for the warehouses needed to be just right: warehouses needed to have navigable water on one side and railroads on the other side.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p = 373 }} The navigable waters needed to give vessels access to any other port in the world. The railroads needed to reach tens of thousands of farms to the west as well to the major consumer cities on the East coast.

Armour fully recognized the site and logistics planning needs. He was a supporter of the railroads and was a stockholder in the CBQ, the Chicago & Northwestern, and the Chicago Milwaukee and St Paul Railroads.{{ sfn | Chicago Tribune | 1881 }} Later he was a director of the ROCK.{{ sfn | Railroad and Warehouse Commission | 1880 | p = 196 }} He was probably one of the few shareholders that had actually laid track. On the canal side, at the Chicago Canal Convention of 1863,{{ sfn | nytimes | 1863 }} Armour was a member of the CBT delegation{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p = 349 }} - most likely one of the few members that had actually dug a canal.

Because of the likelihood of [[dust explosion]]s, grain warehouses were frequent venues for fires. Armour also foresaw the need for fully funded insurance. He was a local director of the [[Liverpool, London and Globe Building|Liverpool & London & Globe Insurance Company]], a director of the Chicago Mutual Insurance Company{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | pp = 641}} and a director of the Merchants Insurance Company.{{ sfn | Chicago Tribune | 1881 }}

By 1870 the remaining impediments to growth were less about the technology and more about legal and political matters. In 1870 the ''Chicago Tribune'' reported:

{{ quote
| text = The name of a Chicago warehouseman has become a synonym with that of a pirate .... It may be safely affirmed that no man voluntarily sends his grain to Chicago who can send it elsewhere. {{ sfn | Chicago Tribune| 1870 }}
}}

== The Chicago Fire and after ==
[[File:Chicago_in_Flames_by_Currier_%26_Ives,_1871.jpg|thumb|left|Chicago in Flames by Currier & Ives, 1871]]
The [[Great Chicago Fire]] "was a conflagration that burned from Sunday, October 8, to early Tuesday, October 10, 1871. The fire killed up to 300 people, destroyed roughly 3.3 square miles (9 km2) of Chicago, Illinois, and left more than 100,000 residents homeless." Armour and his partners apparently came through physically unscathed but their various business affairs were totally disrupted. The offices of Armour, Dole and Co, Munger & Wheeler were destroyed as well as Armour, Dole & Co Elevator "A", the MLTC offices, the Merchants Insurance Company offices - which were exploded to make a fire break that failed - and the CBT offices.

The story of how the MLTC was able to move the bank's funds at the height of the fire is well-described in ''The Advancement of Chicago as a Financial Center up to the Close of the Nineteenth Century''.{{ sfn | MLTC| 1901 | pp = 92-100}} Also described was the setting up of an improvised bank in Solomon A Smith's dining room on Monday, October 9 and recreating all the accounts even with all the banks and most of the customer's records had been destroyed.

The Munn & Scott affair occurred, starting in 1872. See below.

In 1875, Armour was elected president of the CBT.{{ efn | It seems likely Armour's election was in response or somehow related to Armour's benevolence in the Munn & Scott affair.}}{{ sfn | CBT | 1876 }}{{ sfn | Andreas | 1886 | p = 320 }} During his tenure, on January 14, the King of Hawaii visited the CBT trading floor and a racist incident occurred. It was covered in detail by the ''Chicago Tribune''.{{ sfn | Chicago Tribune | 187T5 }} Also during the year, for the first time, memberships could be bought and sold{{ sfn | Cronan | 1991 | p = 137 }} and a committee was instituted to report of the recommendation of situating a US mint in Chicago. The report was an added as an appendix to the CBT annual report.{{ sfn | CBT | 1876 }}

There were few further impediments to growth. By 1885, the capacity of the Armour, Dole & Co grain elevators was 6,350,000 bushels with a total shipping and receiving capacity of 1,500,000 per day. {{ sfn | MacGrath | Reed | 1892 | p = 229 }}

== Munn & Scott affair ==
[[File:1866-chicago-munn-scott-grain-elevators.jpg|thumb|left| Munn & Sccott Grain-Elevators, Chicago 1866]]
The Munn & Scott grain-warehousing company was founded in 1844 in Spring Bay, Illinois, north of Peoria. By 1856, Ira Y. Munn and his partners owned a large Chicago grain elevator with a capacity of 200,000 bushels. George L. Scott joined the enterprise in 1858, and the name was changed name to Munn & Scott. By the end of the Civil War, the company owned four Chicago grain elevators with a total capacity of 2.3 million bushels, nearly a third of the total capacity of all of the city's large elevators.{{ sfn | EncyclopediaChicago - Munn & Scott | 2017 }}{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p = 375 }}{{ sfn | Magrath | 1964 }}

Munn served as president of the Chicago Board of Trade and as president of the city's Chamber of Commerce in 1868. Annual revenues reached about $4 million in 1867; by 1870, the company ranked as the city's leading grain warehouse.{{ sfn | Magrath | 1964 }}

By 1868 Munn & Scott and four other firms - including Armour, Dole and Co - dominated the Chicago grain elevator landscape. They were interlocked in a business pool, each owning part interest in each of the others.
Therefore, they could fix prices and carry out dirty tricks that included fraudulent grading, dishonest weighing, mixing grades, restricting competition, hiding storage information, and issuing false receipts.{{ sfn | Cronan | 1991 | p = 137 }}
Joseph Medill, whose newspaper made warehouse regulation its cause, put it colorfully:

{{ quote 
| text = The fifty million bushels of grain that pass into and out of the city of Chicago ''per annum'', are controlled absolutely by a few warehouse men and the officers of railways. They form the grand ring, that wrings the sweat and blood out of the producers of Illinois. There is no provision in the fundamental law standing between the unrestricted avarice of monopoly and the common rights of the people; but the great, laborious, patient ox, the farmer, is bitten and bled, harassed and tortured, by these rapacious, blood sucking insects.{{ sfn | Ely, Burnham & Bartlett | 1870 | p = 1629 }} 
}}

The Munn & Scott firm was both a prime cause of complaints and a leader in the fight against effective control by the CBT.{{ sfn | Magrath | 1964 }}<br>
In the summer of 1872, the firm was exposed as having massively cheated clients using multiple methods. It was learned that Munn & Scott grain receipts totaling 300,000 bushels were not backed by grain.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p 367-368}}{{ sfn | MarketsWiki - Ira Y Munn  | 2013 }}<br>
Had the Munn & Scott matter had been allowed to take its course, it would have created a panic which would have extended throughout the whole Northwest. Armour, a silent partner in the firm, could probably have entirely escaped, or evaded, any personal responsibility in the matter.{{ sfn | Chicago Tribune | 1881 }} Instead, Armour purchased the Munn interests for $10{{ sfn | Chicago Tribune | 1873 }} and quietly set about purchasing grain to make its receipts good.{{ sfn | taylor | 1917 | pp = 457-460 }}

When a reporter from ''The Tribune'' interviewed him on the subject, Armour declined to say anything in reference to it, but requested as a special favor that no noise be made about it in the paper. He had merely done his duty, he said, and it might interfere with the country's business if it were written up in the newspapers.{{ sfn | Chicago Tribune | 1881 }}
<!--
Adding insult to injury, the firm along with three other speculators then attempted to [[Cornering_the_market| corner the market]] for wheat in Chicago but failed in doing so and went into bankruptcy.
-->
<br>
By this time, the Munn & Scott firm had gone bankrupt in a grain speculation deal, and Ira Munn and George Scott both found that they were now strictly employees of Armour himself.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}

In the same year, Munn & Scott was charged with violating new Illinois regulations that enabled the state to inspect and regulate the elevators. Munn and his company achieved their most lasting fame in 1876–77, when the US Supreme Court in ''[[Munn v. Illinois]]'' rejected Munn's argument that the state had no right to regulate privately owned enterprises such as grain elevators.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1886 | p = 331 }}{{ sfn | EncyclopediaChicago - Munn & Scott | 2017 }}

Following the demise of Munn & Scott and the enactment of new laws and the addition to CBT regulations, the dislike of the "warehousemen" seemed to diminish. There continued to be fraudulent behaviors and attempts were made to corner markets but these appear to have been more the actions of rogue individuals and not due to underlying structural flaws in the warehousing system.

== Personal, political and philanthropic life ==
Armour married Barbara Allison (1826–1898) in the early 1850s. She was born in [[Aberdeen]], Scotland and emigrated to Chicago when she was very young. Their first son John was born in 1851. The first Armour home was on [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]] near Monroe Street.{{sfn|Chicago Tribune|1898}}

The Great Chicago Fire disrupted Armour's personal life. He lost his house, his church, his children's school. He also lost civic projects he had dedicated much time to, including the YMCA, the Seaman's Bethel and Chicago Academy of Design.

After the Chicago Fire, the family built and moved into a new house at 1945 South [[Prairie Avenue]] in 1872.{{ sfn | Tyre| 2008 | p = 27}} They also had a summer house in [[Waukegan]], IL.{{ sfn |Chicago Tribune | 1898}}

While on a voyage to Europe – made with the hope of improving his health – Armour died of rheumatism of the heart in [[Brighton]], [[England]] on June 13, 1881.{{sfn|EncyclopediaChicago - Biographical Dictionary|2017}}{{sfn|USGenWeb|2006}} His body was returned to the US and he was buried at [[Graceland Cemetery]] in Chicago.{{ sfn | findagrave| 2013 }}

=== The arts ===
==== Gallery ====
<gallery mode=packed heights=150 alt="Works of art related to George Armour" >
File:1872-1945-prairie-avenue-looking-north.jpg | Armour residence at 1945 Prairie Avenue, Chicago. IL
File:1863-john-william-armour-painted-by-george-p-a-healy.jpg | ''Portrait of John William Armour'' by G P A Healy, 1863
File:1865-john-william-armour-sculpted-by-unknown.jpg | ''Bas-relief of John William Armour'', 1865
File:1865-barbara-allison-armour-painted-by-sir-lawrence-alma-tadema.jpg | ''Portrait of Barbara Allison Armour'' by Sir Lawrence Alma Tadema, 1865
File:1860s-barbara-allison-armour-photo.jpg | ''Photograph of Barbara Allison Armour'', ''circa'' 1860
File:1894-barbara-allison-armour-etching-by-anders-zorn.jpg | ''Portrait of Barbara Allison Armour'' by Anders Zorn, 1894
</gallery>
By the 1850s, the population of Chicago grew to over 110,000 inhabitants. As with many groups of people this size, the population included artisans, artists and art patrons.

Examples of a love of the arts in Chicago at the time include:
* In 1855 William B Ogden invited [[George Peter Alexander Healy]] to visit Chicago. Healy was an American portrait painter and one of the most prolific and popular painters of his day. He lived and painted in Chicago for the next fourteen years
* The first major art exhibition was held in 1859 and attracted over 12,000 visitors.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p = 514 }}{{ sfn | ihap - First Chicago Art Exhibition | 2017 }}
* The construction of [[Crosby's Opera House]] and its eventual success{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | pp = 601-607}}

The Armours become associated with this artistic milieu by becoming collectors and patrons. Their son John Armour died on May 16, 1865 of a rheumatic heart condition. Some time before that, John's portrait was painted by Healy. Prior to his death, the Armours traveled to Europe hoping to cure John. While in Europe a bas-relief bust of John was sculpted. Also on that voyage a portrait of Barbara Allison Armour was painted by Sir [[Lawrence Alma-Tadema]] in London in 1865.

Also of note, Armour's partner James H Dole had been very active with the Chicago Academy of Design, was a founder of the Chicago Academy of Fine Arts and supported the Art Institute until his death in 1902.{{ sfn | MacGrath | Reed | 1902 | p = 152 }}

The culmination of this participation is that Armour was a founder and elected first President of the [[Chicago Academy of Fine Arts]] in 1879.{{ sfn | aic | 1927 | p = 6 }}{{ sfn | Chicago Tribune| 1880 }}{{ sfn | Andreas | 1886 | p = 421 }}{{ sfn | Currey - Volume 2 | 1912 | p = 264 }} The Academy changed its name to the [[Art Institute of Chicago]] in 1882.

The background in the creation of the Art Institute is complex. The formation of the Institute and its origins in the Chicago Academy of Design are detailed by A T Andreas in his ''History of Chicago - From the Earliest Period to the Present Time''.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1886 | pp = 419-422 }} A darker side of the takeover of assets is covered by Joel S. Dryer in a presentation titled ''The Story You Don't Know About A Place We All Love'' delivered to The Chicago Literary Club May 14, 2001.{{ sfn| ihap - Art Institute of Chicago | 2017 }} Further investigations has been carried out by Kirsten M. Jensen in her book: ''The American Salon: The Art Gallery at the Chicago Interstate Industrial Exposition, 1873--1890''.{{sfn | Jensen| 2007 }}

=== Church obligations ===
Armour was active with the [[Second Presbyterian Church (Chicago)|Second Presbyterian Church]] and along with his good friend Norman Williams - a prominent Chicago lawyer.{{ sfn | Second Presbyterian Church | 1892 | pp = 46-47 }} 
He was a Trustee and an Elder of the church. The first church was destroyed in the Chicago Fire of 1871. A new church was completed by 1874. Armour donated the tower which was completed in 1884 after Armour's death.{{ sfn | Tyre| 2008 | p = 68 }}

Armour donated $500 toward the construction of the Willow Creek Presbyterian Church in Argyle, IL in 1877.{{ sfn | Harvey | 1924 | p = 14 }}

=== Civic duties ===
On March 22, 1858, Chicagoans again gathered in an attempt to form a [[YMCA]]. After a series of meetings, a constitution was written and the first YMCA of Chicago was officially formed.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p = 511 }} Armour was a founder and trustee of the YMCA of Chicago.{{ sfn| Stockwell | 1992 | pp = 421-422 }}

Armour was a founder and member of the [[Commercial Club of Chicago]] in 1878. A group of successful Chicago businessmen, the Commercial Club promoted the economic development of the city. The Commercial Club patterned itself after traditional civic improvement clubs, holding regular meetings to discuss pertinent reform issues of the day.{{sfn|Commercial Club|1904| p = 21}}{{sfn|EncyclopediaChicago - Commercial Club of Chicago|2017}}

Armour dedicated a [[:File:George Armour Sculpture - geograph.org.uk - 615575.jpg| Fountain in Campbeltown, Scotland]] - his birthplace - in 1881. See below.

=== Politics ===
Armour was attacked in during the elections of 1857.{{ sfn | Chicago Tribune | 1881 | p = 159 }} Widespread "rioting and knockdowns" were reported in the predominantly Irish-Democratic 7th Ward in the final days of the March 2, 1857 mayoral election.{{sfn| ispn | 1995 }} The ''Illinois Police & Sheriff's News'' described the event as follows:

{{ quote
| text = A Republican businessman named George Armour challenged the votes of some Irishmen who did not reside within ward boundaries. Armour was set upon by a crowd of poll-watching ruffians, kicked, beaten about the head, and dragged through the streets by the hair until his friends came to the rescue. Another Wentworth worker was not nearly so lucky. He was attacked, stabbed, and chased clear down to La Salle Street where he jumped onto a dangerously thin sheet of river ice to escape his pursuers. The man escaped but not before one of the 7th Ward Irishers crashed through the ice and drowned in the bone-chilling waters of the Chicago River.{{sfn| ispn | 1995 }}
}}
The only political position Armour ever held was that of elector in the [[Electoral College (United States)|Electoral College]] for the Hayes ticket in 1876. Special attention was called to him at the time, from the fact that his right to hold the place was challenged. It was alleged that he'd never been naturalized and consequently was ineligible. If true this would have lost Illinois one of her votes and tied the result in the Electoral College. After some difficulty, however, Armour was able to find a record of his naturalization, and he cast his vote along with his colleagues, for Hayes and Wheeler.{{ sfn | Chicago Tribune | 1881 }}

