==== Banks too big to fail ====
Not all of Armour's efforts ended up with the legacies that he might have wanted. Armour's and his partners' goals in founding MLTC was to set up under the charter of being a very safe and secure banking operation. Under this charter the bank grew for decades, eventually the bank grew to be the biggest bank in Chicago and among the biggest in the US - [[Continental Illinois]]. Unfortunately in the late eighties the bank started growing so big and too fast that it failed. The Federal Reserve saved Continental Illinois - because it was "[[too big to fail]]".

==== Trading pit racism ====
When the King of Hawaii visited the CBT trading floor on January 14, 1875, the traders in the pits began to sing a song titled "The King of Cannibal Island". Armour repeatedly banged his gavel and shouted "Shame!" to little avail. To this day brokers and trading bits remain as venues where racism and discrimination continue to exist - regardless of management attempts to stop this behavior.
<!--
Citations to be added:
* {{ URL | http://www.cnbc.com/id/100993918 }}
* {{ URL | http://www.wallstreetoasis.com/blog/quick-thoughts-%E2%80%93-racism-on-wall-street }} -->

==== Effective movement of bulk materials ====
Having taken part building some of the first railroads and canals in the US, Armour understood the need for systems that would enable the movement of bulk materials around the world. He always built his warehouses at the junctions between the two modes of transport.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p = 373 }} Today grain elevators are still built between navigable waters and railroad lines. And, even more impressive, the [[container terminal]]s of the world - "where cargo containers are transshipped between different transport vehicles, for onward transportation" - all follow the same planning that George Armour used.

==== Military-industrial complex ====
Just at the beginning of the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], a meeting was called by CBT with the express purpose of funding the establishment of a brigade to support the Union side.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885  | p = 162 }} Most of the units were infantry, but there were also [[Zouave#Zouaves of the American Civil War|zouaves]] and [[cavalry]]. In those days the most prestigious units were cavalry. Given that CBT members were among the most prosperous men of the city, it might seen logical that they would sponsor a cavalry unit, but no they formed an artillery unit - a unit that could use products made in Chicago by their own members.{{ sfn | taylor | 1917 | p = 281 }} The legacy is that today we call this the [[military-industrial complex]] - "an informal alliance between a nation's military and the arms industry which supplies it, seen together as a vested interest which influences public policy. A driving factor behind this relationship between the government and defense-minded corporations is that both sides benefit--one side from obtaining war weapons, and the other from being paid to supply them."

==== Non-sectarian support ====
Armour was a devout Presbyterian and an elder of his church.{{ sfn | Second Presbyterian Church | 1892 | p66 }} The development of his business, however, depended on people of all faiths who were healthy in "mind, body and spirit". An early effort to provide education, fitness and development that superseded religious boundaries was the [[YMCA]]. Armour was a trustee of Farwell Hall - which housed the early Chicago YMCA - in 1861 and then he was elected a director of the YMCA itself in 1867. Today the YMCA of Metro Chicago has 23 centers, five camps and hundreds of extension sites to meet the changing needs of the more than 200,000 members served every year.{{ sfn | YMCA of Metro Chicago | 2017 }}

He also seems to have been involved with the what is now the Bethel African Methodist Episcopal Church - Chicago's third oldest Black church.{{ sfn | Andreas | 1885 | p = 445 }}
<!--
