{{Italictitle}}
'''''Loomis v. Wisconsin''''' was a petition to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] to overturn the previous [[Wisconsin Supreme Court]] ruling in ''State v. Loomis''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/loomis-v-wisconsin/|title=Loomis v. Wisconsin - SCOTUSblog|work=SCOTUSblog|access-date=2017-05-05|language=en-US}}</ref> The case challenged the State of [[Wisconsin]]'s use of proprietary, closed-source risk assessment software in the sentencing of Eric Loomis to six years in prison.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/23/us/backlash-in-wisconsin-against-using-data-to-foretell-defendants-futures.html|title=In Wisconsin, a Backlash Against Using Data to Foretell Defendants’ Futures|last=Smith|first=Mitch|date=2016-06-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-05-05|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The case alleged that using such software in sentencing violates the defendant's right to due process because it prevents the defendant from challenging the scientific validity and accuracy of such test.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://harvardlawreview.org/2017/03/state-v-loomis/|title=State v. Loomis|website=harvardlawreview.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-05}}</ref> The case also alleged that the system in question ("Correctional Offender Management Profiling for Alternative Sanctions" or [[COMPAS (software)|COMPAS]]) violates due process rights by taking gender and race into account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/wi-supreme-court/1742124.html|title=FindLaw's Supreme Court of Wisconsin case and opinions.|website=Findlaw|access-date=2017-05-05}}</ref> Hearing this case would have given the court "the opportunity to rule on whether it violates due process to sentence someone based on a risk-assessment instrument whose workings are protected as a trade secret."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/13/opinion/how-computers-are-harming-criminal-justice.html|title=Opinion {{!}} When a Computer Program Keeps You in Jail|last=Wexler|first=Rebecca|date=2017-06-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-09-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

The Supreme Court denied the writ of certiorari, thus declining to hear the case, on June 26, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/062617zor_8759.pdf|title=Supreme Court Order List (06/26/2017)|last=|first=|date=|website=Supreme Court of the United States|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/docketfiles/16-6387.htm|title=Docket for 16-6387|website=www.supremecourt.gov|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref>

