{{Unsourced|date=June 2013}}

In '''''S v Nkondo''''' (2000), an important case in [[South Africa|South African]] [[Criminal procedure in South Africa|criminal procedure]], Nkondo had appeared before a regional [[court]] and was convicted of [[rape]] and [[robbery]]. The case was then sent to the [[High Courts of South Africa|high court]] for sentencing where it was held that N had not been thoroughly apprised of his [[Right to counsel|right to legal representation]] and had elected to appear in person.

The court held that when courts explain the right to legal representation to accused persons and an accused person facing a serious charge elects to remain unrepresented, the [[magistrate]] should ask the accused why he or she wanted to appear in person and if it appeared that the accused was under some or other misunderstanding that has to be put right.

The High Court set aside the [[Verdict|convictions]] of robbery and rape and [[Remand (court procedure)|remitted]] the matter to the regional court in order that the matter could be re-tried.

